metadata.name: Southern Gothic #52
metadata.description:
“Southern Gothic” is my debut release on the fxhash platform. The project is created entirely through code. All copyrights are released to the holder of each image output, even for commercial purposes.

“Southern Gothic” borrows its name from the literary genre made famous by writers like Flannery O’Connor and Carson McCullers. Rather than illustrating a singular setting, the code generates an entire rural townscape, thereby, blurring the boundaries between representation and narrative. The individual scenes are framed frontally with an intentionally flat aesthetic character, referencing traditional folk art of the American South. The absence of human figures within these scenes adds to their overwhelming sense of darkness and forlorn. Observing multiple scenes side-by-side, one may even get the strange feeling that something terrible has happened (or is about to happen) in this rural landscape.

Pressing the down arrow saves the coded output as a .png image.

metadata.name: Iteration is Usually Recursive (Pt. 1) #151
metadata.description:
This is the companion piece released with 'Iteration is Usually Recursive — Introduction: Finding answers in pre-computational art', the first in a series of essays, some long, some short, on generative art, theory and the practitioners of the medium. 

This piece started a simple experimen recreating George Nees’ Schotter (1968)— a classic piece of generative art history — as vanilla js SVG graphics. From there, I specifically developed it with non-plotter printing in mind, and more specific still, Riso Printing (think a scanner with a digital screen-printer MacGyver’d on). The palettes are taken from hex-estimated Risograph colour gamuts, with three layers being multiplied together to replicate, to some degree, the blending of the semi-transparent Risographic inks. Within this study, there’s a few different things going on, the initial setup is rectangles which cascade down the canvas, inheriting more extreme rotation as they get closer to the bottom (a la Schotter). The second is a subdivision of the shapes with filled circled, outlined circles and squares — since in this study the base shapes are rectangles and not squares, distribution of the ‘dithering’ can be larger than a single ‘pixel’ size — when these multiple layers overlap, the shapes produce a halftone-moire effect, forms and structures appear from the noise as the underlying patterns intersect. 

tx: Who?, Cosimo, Liam Egan, Andreas Rau, Louis

Licensing: CC-BY-NC-ND

metadata.name: Plottable Thousands #64
metadata.description:
'Thousands' explores the packing of recursive circles and golden angle spirals distributing various particles on a A4 canvas.

A SVG file can be exported (right click save) to plot the piece physically.

You can enjoy the digital version that simulate ink effects and optional, thanks to the utility token decoupling, get a physical one: the digital NFT is the recipe to a plottable art piece, owning it confers the right to plot or request a physical plot from @greweb (https://greweb.me/plots/nft). @greweb would use fountain pens but other plotting artists are free to achieve it with their own materials and ship to collectors – as long as NFT is owned at request time.

Code: https://github.com/gre/gre/tree/master/doodles/plottable-thousands

@greweb – 2022 – tech: WebGL + Rust + WASM – CC BY-SA 4.0 https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0/

metadata.name: Focal Point #44
metadata.description:
The "Focal Point" series showcases a unique combination of four square artworks arranged in the shape of a plus sign on a textured brown paper. The central motif present in each artwork is an anchor, which also serves as the basis for the color palette throughout the series. The artist began by digitally creating a precisionist central artwork which led to further creation of 28 total artworks, divided into four sets, each set representing a direction.

The symmetry of the resulting form is striking, with the four squares perfectly aligning to create a cohesive and balanced composition. The use of textured brown paper as the background adds depth and dimension to the series, creating an interesting contrast with the clean lines and geometric shapes of the artworks.

The series is an exploration of unity and balance, using the plus sign, a symbol of addition, congruence and equilibrium, to visually represent the idea that by bringing different elements together, a new and harmonious whole can be formed. 

The artist's intent is to convey that despite our differences in physical and intellectual attributes, we are all the same at our core. 

20% of the proceeds from this project will be donated to Southern Exposure, an artist-centered non-profit organization committed to supporting visual artists, that has been in the San Francisco Bay Area since 1974.

For more information regarding my past and upcoming projects, please visit meditationsincolor.com.

metadata.name: WatSplash #4
metadata.description:
Water Splash is a stunning piece of art that captures the beauty and "movement" of watercolors, the piece features multiple drops of watercolors as it falls from a "faucet" and creates a splash upon impact. The bright colors and bold brushstrokes used in the painting add to its dynamism and energy.

Overall, Water Splash is a breathtaking work of art that is sure to impress and inspire.

I hope you enjoy it!

metadata.name: This is Not an Image #33
metadata.description:
When you see a piece of generative art, you are looking at a meta-message, an image whose value is not of form but of subtext. These images are a collision and reformation of ideas and conceptual histories between artists Nudoru and Sub Net. This dichotomy reminds us of the painting "The Treachery of Images" by René Magritte, where he paints a picture of a pipe but states underneath, "ceci n'est pas une pipe" (This is not a pipe), meaning that there is a schism between what a thing is and what it represents. What is unique about these works go beyond the images and text combinations themselves. It is about how images create new thoughts not by not pretending to be completely novel but that builds upon one another in a system of complex synthesis.

This token is part of the Floor Exhibit co-curated by the NFT Museum of Newberry, SC and Fort Gallery NFT.

Viewing in desktop Chrome is recommended for the best results.
Press' p' to pause/resume.
Press' s' to save a screenshot. The image size is 2357 × 3000px.

metadata.name: AERO #117
metadata.description:
AERO

In the stillness of the void, floating cities hang suspended, bound by no earthly gravity. The buildings, wrought in shades of dreamy pastels, appear as though they have been plucked from some other time and place, and set adrift in a new and unknowable realm.

Here, amidst the stillness and silence, ropes hang loosely like vines, connecting the structures in a delicate web of possibility. The architecture of the buildings is vaguely familiar, yet strangely surreal, hinting at a past now forgotten.

As the eye wanders through this landscape of suspended structures, a feeling of nostalgia begins to seep in. There is a sense that these cities were once inhabited, bustling with the energy of human life. Now, they stand alone, abandoned and forgotten, as nature slowly reclaims its territory.



The AERO series explores how a minimalistic set of shapes and rules can be extrapolated to create complex assemblies, the same way individual buildings will form villages and cities.

To add a sense of organic texture to these geometric structures, ropes that connect certain squares have been added. They can sometimes take on the appearance of vines. This addition aims creates a sense of tension between the man-made and the natural.



Double click or double tap to save the current image

In fullscreen mode / live view:
Add "&size=xxxx" at the end of the url to generate a custom sized image
Add "&clean" at the end of the url to remove the grain effect


Artist: Estienne
Feb. 2023
